          "body": "The town-lament of verses 10-15 is one of the most rhetorically sophisticated passages in the Minor Prophets. Micah addresses a string of Shephelah towns — his own region, the landscape he grew up in — and each address is a paronomasia, a Hebrew pun in which the town's name becomes its epitaph. Beth-le-aphrah (house of dust) — roll in the dust. Shaphir (beautiful city) — depart in shameful nakedness. Zaanan (place of going out) — does not go out. Achzib (deception) — will prove deceptive to the kings of Israel. Mareshah (possession) — a conqueror will come for you. The effect is devastating: the very names the inhabitants boasted in become the names of their disgrace. This is the rhetorical equivalent of Micah standing in each town square and announcing: your name is your judgment. The mention of Lachish in verse 13 is particularly significant — Lachish was the second-largest city in Judah, a major military fortress, the city Sennacherib would later depict in gloating relief-carvings on his palace walls. Micah accuses it of being 'the beginning of sin to the daughter of Zion' — the conduit by which northern Israel's rebellious acts traveled southward into Judah. Geography becomes moral biography."
