      {
        "number": 4,
        "title": "The town-lament — names become epitaphs along the invasion corridor",
        "range": "1:10-15",
        "excerpt": "Tell it not in Gath, weep not at all. At Beth-le-aphrah roll yourself in the dust.",
        "body": "The town-lament of verses 10-15 is one of the most technically accomplished passages in the Hebrew prophets. Its opening allusion — 'Tell it not in Gath' — quotes David's lament over Saul and Jonathan from 2 Samuel 1:20 almost verbatim. David's original concern was that the Philistines of Gath would rejoice over Israel's defeat. Micah inverts the reference: by Micah's time, Gath had already fallen to Hazael of Syria (2 Kings 12:17) and was no longer a Philistine threat. The allusion is therefore nostalgic and bitter — Micah cites the lament formula for a nation that is itself already gone, implying that Israel's humiliation will be at least as complete as Gath's.\n\nWhat follows is a cascade of Hebrew wordplays (paronomasia) in which each town's name is weaponized as its own judgment. The wordplays are nearly untranslatable but were immediately recognizable to a Hebrew-speaking audience who knew the landscape. Beth-le-aphrah means 'house of dust' — roll in the dust. Shaphir means 'beauty' — depart in shameful nakedness. Zaanan sounds like the verb 'to go out' — does not go out. Beth-ezel suggests 'house of what is beside' — its support is taken away. Maroth sounds like 'bitter' — waits in bitter futility for good. Lachish sounds like the word for 'team of horses' — harness the chariot, flee with your horses. Achzib sounds like the word for 'deception' (akhzav) — will prove a deception to Israel's kings. Mareshah sounds like 'possession' — a new possessor is coming. The cumulative effect is a prophetic funeral march through Micah's own homeland, in which every name is pronounced as a sentence.\n\nLachish receives the sharpest indictment: it was 'the beginning of sin to the daughter of Zion' (1:13). This is historically precise — Lachish sat astride the main road between the northern kingdom and the Judean heartland. It was the city through which northern influences, commercial networks, and religious innovations traveled south into Judah. Archaeologically, Lachish has yielded evidence of significant Assyrian-period destruction; Sennacherib boasted of its conquest in a room of his Nineveh palace devoted entirely to the siege's depiction. Micah names it before the fact. Adullam in verse 15 — the cave of David's fugitive years (1 Samuel 22:1) — closes the lament with one last bitter irony: Israel's glory will enter Adullam, meaning the leaders of the nation will be reduced to hiding in a cave like a hunted king.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** The paronomasia across verses 10-15 is a recognized prophetic rhetorical device in which the prophet exploits the phonological resonance of place names to embed the judgment in the landscape itself. The technique appears also in Zephaniah 2:4 and Amos 5:5. Commentators from Hilary of Poitiers to Francis Andersen have noted that the wordplays function as a mnemonic — the audience would repeat the names and re-hear the verdict every time they spoke the geography."
      },
      {
        "number": 5,
        "title": "Exile as covenant finality — the children depart",
        "range": "1:16",
        "excerpt": "Make yourself bald and cut off your hair, because of the children of your delight; extend your baldness like the eagle, for they will go from you into exile.",
        "body": "The final verse of Micah 1 shifts address from individual towns to the community as a whole — a corporate second-person feminine singular (addressing Daughter Zion as a collective). The command is to perform the most extreme form of mourning in the ancient Near Eastern repertoire: shave the head completely. Head-shaving for mourning the dead appears in Job 1:20, Isaiah 15:2, Jeremiah 16:6, Ezekiel 7:18, and Amos 8:10. The Mosaic law actually restricted it for priests (Leviticus 21:5) and for Israel as a whole in certain contexts (Deuteronomy 14:1), precisely because it was associated with pagan mourning rites. That Micah commands it unrestrictedly signals the extremity of the coming loss — a loss so total that even the ritual restrictions are set aside by the weight of the grief.\n\nThe simile of the eagle is multilayered. The Hebrew nesher can refer to either the eagle or the griffon vulture; both are known for their striking bare head. The baldness of the eagle in molting season was proverbially extreme (hence the English 'bald eagle'). But the eagle in the Old Testament is also the symbol of Yahweh's own care for Israel — Deuteronomy 32:11 pictures God as an eagle carrying Israel on His wings. To command Israel to mourn 'like the eagle' is to strip the symbol of its comfort. The wings that once carried the nation now mirror back the nation's grief.\n\nThe cause named is 'the children of your delight' (literally 'children of your luxuries' or 'darlings'). The exile of children is the covenant's most personal curse — Deuteronomy 28:32, 41 specifically names seeing your children taken captive as the anguish of covenant failure. For a culture in which children were the continuity of family, covenant, land, and name, their deportation was not merely demographic loss but existential erasure. 'They will go from you into exile' — galah, the same verb of exposure and removal that anchored the Samaria verdict in verse 6. John Calvin noted that Micah ends the chapter on this word deliberately: the uncovering of Samaria's foundations and the removal of Judah's children are the same divine act, the same covenant Lord executing the same covenant sanctions from the same place. The chapter that began with God coming down from His holy temple ends with His people going out from their holy land.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Galah* (exile, v.16) is from the same root as *galah* (lay bare, expose) in verse 6. The chapter is bookended by the same verb: God exposes Samaria's foundations (galah, v.6); Israel's children go into exile (galah, v.16). The structural echo is intentional — the same act of divine uncovering operates at both ends of the chapter, against the city and against the community."
      }
